  1. The data table Births78 in mosaicData package gives a day by day record of the number of births in the United States in 1978. Use the data() function to load this dataset and view the data set using the function head().
date births dayofyear wday

  1. The date variable in Birth78 prints out in the conventional, human-readable way. The lubridate package contains helpful functions that will extract various information about any date. For this assignment you will need to use the function lubridate::month(date) which gives you the month from date. Use the optional argument label=TRUE to have the month spelled out rather than given as a number 1-12. For example:
head(Births78$date)
## [1] "1978-01-01 UTC" "1978-01-02 UTC" "1978-01-03 UTC" "1978-01-04 UTC"
## [5] "1978-01-05 UTC" "1978-01-06 UTC"
head(month(Births78$date, label=TRUE))
## [1] Jan Jan Jan Jan Jan Jan
## 12 Levels: Jan < Feb < Mar < Apr < May < Jun < Jul < Aug < Sep < ... < Dec

For purposes of clarity later, we will rename wday as Wday using rename():

myBirths78 <- Births78 %>% rename(Wday=wday)
head(myBirths78)
date births dayofyear Wday
1978-01-01 7701 1 Sun
1978-01-02 7527 2 Mon
1978-01-03 8825 3 Tues
1978-01-04 8859 4 Wed
1978-01-05 9043 5 Thurs
1978-01-06 9208 6 Fri

  1. Lets introduce another dataset to our graph. You can find a data set listing US federal holidays at http://tiny.cc/dcf/US-Holidays.csv. Read it in as follows:1

  1. The point of the lubridate::dmy() function is to convert the character-string date stored in the CSV to a POSIX date format that automatically respects the order of time.↩
